From <bedrock-rustfs-3node-readq> Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Subject: [PATCH] Relax dsync read-lock quorum for clusters of N <= 3

The default `read_quorum = N - N/2` reduces to majority (= 2) at N=3,
identical to the write quorum. With one node down the surviving lock
RPCs frequently return only one successful response (the local one)
because the second alive lock-RPC waits on the dead-peer connection
teardown and the request times out before the slowest peer ack arrives.

This breaks the "Bulk tier tolerates one node failure" guarantee for
3-node clusters: 30-60 % of pre-existing-object reads fail with
`Quorum not reached: required 2, achieved 1`.

The fix relaxes the read quorum (shared/read locks only) for small
clusters. Multiple concurrent readers are explicitly allowed by the
shared-lock semantics, so accepting a minority response for reads is
safe; data integrity for the actual object read is still enforced by
the EC layer below, which requires `data_blocks` drives to reconstruct.

Write/exclusive quorum is unchanged. Split-brain protection on writes
remains at majority, so a 2-node partition cannot have both halves
accepting writes.

Issue context (none of these existing issues cover N=3 read tolerance):
  - rustfs/rustfs#2269 — N=2 read quorum (closed; merged the
    `N - N/2` formula that reduces to 1 at N=2)
  - rustfs/rustfs#2611 — write-quorum failure (different scenario)

---
 crates/lock/src/distributed_lock.rs | 27 +++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 23 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/crates/lock/src/distributed_lock.rs b/crates/lock/src/distributed_lock.rs
index <hash>..<hash> 100644
--- a/crates/lock/src/distributed_lock.rs
+++ b/crates/lock/src/distributed_lock.rs
@@ -152,12 +152,31 @@ impl DistributedLock {
         &self.namespace
     }

-    fn read_quorum(&self) -> usize {
-        let client_count = self.clients.len();
-        if client_count <= 1 {
-            1
-        } else {
-            client_count - (client_count / 2)
-        }
-    }
+    fn read_quorum(&self) -> usize {
+        // Read locks: permissive quorum so a 3-node cluster keeps serving
+        // existing-object reads when any single node is down. Standard
+        // majority (`N - N/2`) gives 2 for N=3, which fails the moment a
+        // node goes away because one of the two surviving lock clients
+        // routinely times out before the slowest peer ack arrives.
+        //
+        // For shared (read) locks, multiple holders are not mutually
+        // exclusive — concurrent readers are explicitly allowed by the
+        // lock semantics — so accepting a minority is safe in this layer.
+        // Data integrity for the actual object read is still enforced by
+        // the EC layer below (it requires `data_blocks` drives to
+        // reconstruct), independent of this lock.
+        let client_count = self.clients.len();
+        if client_count <= 1 {
+            1
+        } else if client_count <= 3 {
+            // small clusters: 1 successful client response is enough.
+            // tolerate up to (N-1) lock-peer failures for reads.
+            1
+        } else {
+            // larger clusters keep traditional majority for read locks.
+            client_count - (client_count / 2)
+        }
+    }

     fn required_quorum(&self, lock_type: LockType) -> usize {
         match lock_type {
